In Season 6 of PARK’d, we took a jet boat out to Bear Glacier Lagoon, kayaked through icebergs the size of houses to reach the Harding Icefield’s largest glacier, then took a helicopter back to Seward, Alaska. 

Bear glacier is the largest glacier in Kenai Fjords National Park. The range of color in the icebergs is determined by the density of ice that makes up the masses in the water. Depending on how they’re melting, the icebergs could break apart or capsize at any moment. When you observe an iceberg from above the water you might not think it looks that big…but 90% of the iceberg’s mass is below the water’s surface. The crew and I had the unique opportunity to paddle through the lagoon to see of that incredible science up close. Check out season 6 of PARK’d for more! @foxnation

Reminiscing about checking off ice climbing from my bucket list after our incredible day with Exit Glacier Guides in Kenai Fjords National Park. @rosemcadoo and @tkreznar took us straight up a mountain, helped me throw on some crampons and we walked right onto Exit Glacier. Once we made it to the crevasse, Rose lowered me down so I could ice pick my way back out. Nature is so neat 👏🏻 You can catch Season 6 of PARK’d on @foxnation! 

📸: @bud_knapp @carolinaaa_gonz  @shotbyblazefox

Exit Glacier is one of the many reasons why Kenai Fjords National Park is at the top of my favorite national parks list. It flows from Harding Ice Field and in just a few miles, it descends about 3,000 feet…

In Season 6 of PARK’d, we hiked to Exit Glacier and after gearing up, we traversed its surface to reach a crevasse. 

A crevasse is formed when different parts of a glacier move at different speeds. Glaciers tend to move faster in the middle, so the sides of the glacier are slowed down as they scrape against valley walls. When this happens, it creates large gaps in the ice. 

That’s what @rosemcadoo and @tkreznar lowered me into so I could ice pick my way out. Thank you @exitglacierguides for the experience of a lifetime! You can catch the entire hike on @foxnation

📸: @bud_knapp @shotbyblazefox @carolinaaa_gonz

I got the amazing opportunity to go to Space Camp and you can watch it now on @foxnation! Over the course of 3 days, I became an honorary astronaut and learned how what we do in space really affects our daily lives. 

When you think about outer space, you might not think of Huntsville, Alabama, but it’s incredibly important to our nation’s illustrious space program. It’s also home to the U.S. Space and Rocket Center, where you can see how some of our greatest minds developed technology to send the first American satellite into orbit and the first human beings to the moon.

The work that’s still being done there today plays such a significant role in the advancement of space exploration for our entire country and I’m so lucky to have witnessed just a small part of it. 

Apollo astronaut John Young, once said “The dream is still alive,” and after going to space camp, I really felt the  magnitude of those words. I hope you watch this special and feel like you’re along on the journey with me! “Abby Goes to Space Camp” is out now!

In honor of Earth Day, we are celebrating the national park that started it all. Yellowstone epitomizes the unparalleled beauty of nature we have in our country. 

Since 1872, the @nationalparkservice has preserved one of the last and largest natural ecosystems in the temperate zone of Earth. That means over 10,000 hydrothermal features, pristine wilderness, and the habitats of the grizzly bear, wolf and free-ranging herds of elk + bison. 

Today, as we should every day, we give a nod to some of God’s greatest work 🏔️ 

You can watch this special edition if PARK’d in Yellowstone on @foxnation! @bud_knapp @pontiac26 @romono.3 @carrieflatley @ribbleeffect @shotbyblazefox did such an incredible job on this!

In Season 7 of PARK’d, we finally checked off the Half Dome hike at Yosemite! Park Rangers say this is one of the longest and steepest day hikes you’ll encounter in any national park. It has a mountaineering component that involves scaling the granite surface of Half Dome using cables to get 360 views of the park. Throughout the 19-miles and 5,000 feet in elevation gain, we witnessed the beauty of Vernal Fall, the Merced River, Little Yosemite Valley, Sub-dome and the view from the top of Half Dome after we climbed up the cables…all things we can’t wait to show off when this episode airs in November. 

Thank you to the incredible PARK’d team for making this happen, especially @budknapp for saying yes to doing it with me even though I intentionally left out all of the details of the hike 🤷🏼‍♀️ PARK’d Season 7 coming to @foxnation in November! 

#halfdome #yosemite #yosemitenationalpark
19 miles of waterfalls, granite cliffs, wildlife and a lot of huffing & puffing.  You can watch me and @bud_knapp journey to the top of Half Dome in PARK’d: Yosemite coming to @foxnation in November!

Yosemite National Park featured in Season 7 of PARK’d coming soon!

#1/#2: Tunnel View
*This is one of the most photographed viewpoints in the park. From here, you have an unobstructed view of Yosemite Valley which is surrounded by El Capitan, Half Dome and Bridalveil Fall. The tunnel is called the Wawona Tunnel…before the construction of the tunnel the area was known as “Inspiration Point.”

#3/4 Yosemite Falls
*With a height of just over 2400 feet, this is one of the world’s tallest waterfalls and is made up of 3 separate falls…Upper Yosemite Fall, Middle Cascades and Lower Yosemite Fall.

The source of the water is Yosemite Creek, which is fed by the melting snow and glaciers in the Sierra Nevada’s high country.

Not only is it significant to people from all over the world who come to see its beauty, but there’s also cultural significance to the local Native American tribes who consider it a sacred place and still conduct traditional ceremonies in the area.

#5 Glacier Point
*From here, you can see Yosemite Valley, Half Dome, Yosemite Falls AND the High Sierra peaks from an elevation of a little over 7,200 feet above sea level. This viewpoint sits on top of ancient glacial moraines, aka deposits of rocks and debris that have been left behind by retreating glaciers during past ice ages.

This point has been a popular destination for visitors since the late 1800s, but back then, tourists would make the arduous journey on horseback or in horse-drawn carriages.

#7 Half Dome
*Half dome is a granite dome formed by glacial and erosional forces over the course of millions of years. The granite is called “adamellite” and has contributed to the formation’s name “Half Dome.” The granite face towers more than 4700 feet over the floor of the valley .
 
#8 This is the view on top of Half Dome after a full day hike ending with a mountaineering component that took us up cables drilled into the side of the cliff.

Rocky Mountain National Park is known as the “Land of Extremes” partly because the Continental Divide runs through the park marking a climatic division…meaning you experience a range of ecological zones that feature everything from meadows, to alpine lakes (this one is Lake Haiyaha,) to views of the alpine tundra. It’s one of the highest national parks in the nation with elevations of ~7,800 feet to over 14,200 feet. We explore as much of it as we can in Season 7 of PARK’d coming to @foxnation soon! 🎥 BTS: @budknapp
